merits of Christ, by which man pays off his debt to God in Purgatory
to which the angel holds the keys, and at the same time the 'eternal
wealth' of Paradise to which St. Peter holds the keys (^Par~. XIX.11;
XXIII.133-139). The sacredness of this door is in fact emphasized (vv.
130, 134), and since the treasury of Purgatory surpasses the greatest
classical equivalent, it is in effect supernatural. The door leads to
a spiritual ^mons pietatis~ (a pawnbroker's fund, literaly 'a mountain
of piety'), a supernatural treasure created by Christ's infinite act
of satisfaction so that man can redeem the pledge of his soul by paying
his debt to God with the money to make satisfaction, and through which
man can regain full use of the treasure of his free will and obtain the
supreme riches of heaven which, unlike earthly riches, are increased the
more they are shared. Unlike the treasure of Rome, which passed away,
